TY  - JOUR
AU  - DeMarzo, Peter M.
AU  - Duffie, Darrell
T1  - Corporate Incentives for Hedging and Hedge Accounting
PY  - 1995
Y1  - 1995/07/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/8.3.743
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 8
IS  - 3
SP  - 743
EP  - 771
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - This article explores the information effect of financial risk management. Financial hedging improves the informativeness of corporate earnings as a signal of management ability and project quality by eliminating extraneous noise. Managerial and shareholder incentives regarding information transmission may differ, however, leading to conflicts regarding an optimal hedging policy. We show that these incentives depend on the accounting information made available by the firm. Under some circumstances, if hedge transactions are not disclosed (i.e., firms report only aggregate earnings), managers hedge to achieve greater risk reduction than they would if full disclosure were required. In these cases, it is optimal for shareholders to request only aggregate accounting reports.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/8.3.743
ER  - 



